  "hasSensitivityAnalysis": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/sensitivity/cpb-hemolysis-sa",
    "type": "SensitivityAnalysis",
    "name": "Sensitivity analysis: hemolysis response to operating and geometric parameters",
    "description": "One-at-a-time and variance-based (Sobol) sensitivity analyses were conducted varying flow rate (1–7 L/min), rotational speed (1500–3500 RPM), impeller tip clearance (0.15–0.45 mm), and blood viscosity (2.7–4.2 mPa·s). NIH exhibited strongest first-order sensitivity to tip clearance (S1 = 0.41) and rotational speed (S1 = 0.33); flow rate and viscosity contributed S1 = 0.18 and 0.08 respectively. Interaction terms between clearance and speed accounted for an additional 12% of variance, confirming that worst-case hemolysis occurs at minimum clearance and maximum speed, which was adopted as the design-critical operating point for the regulatory decision."
  },
